Use ANSI SQL Statements in Data Cloud

When using Calculated Insights in Data Cloud, provide an eligible ANSI SQL statement. Certain ANSI SQL aggregates and functions are surfaced for this purpose.

REQUIRED EDITIONS
Available in: Lightning Experience

You define a calculated insight with SQL statements that use a specific structure.

SELECT <Attributes>, <Aggregation[_Measures_]> 
FROM <Data Model Object>
JOIN [Inner | Left | Right | Full] <Data Model Object> [Optional]
WHERE <predicate on rows> [Optional]
GROUP BY <columns[_Dimensions_]>


A measure contains quantitative aggregated values that you can measure, for example, the average and total amount.

A dimension contains qualitative values, such as the product name, date, and profile ID. You can use dimensions to categorize your measures.

For a calculated insight to appear in Segments, add the table that you segment on to the query as a JOIN. The primary key of the segmented table must be a dimension in your calculated insight. See the example queries in our Github Repo for reference.

Function Library

You can add a calculated insight to the Function Library for future access. In the Function Library, you can scroll through functions, such as aggregation and datetime. To insert a function, place your cursor at the desired location in your statement and then insert it.

EXAMPLE
SELECT
SUM(SALESORDER__dlm.grand_total_amount__c) as TotalOrderAmount__c,
Individual__dlm.Id__c as CustomerId__c
FROM SALESORDER__dlm
LEFT JOIN Individual__dlm ON SALESORDER__dlm.partyid__c = Individual__dlm.Id__c
WHERE SALESORDER__dlm.tax_rate__c > 5 
GROUP BY CustomerId__c 

Aggregate Functions
An aggregate function performs a calculation on a set of values in Data Cloud and returns a single value.
Case Statements
Handle complex logic as you build advanced metrics with Insights Builder. Use a case statement to get values based on certain conditions. You can use a case in any statement that allows a valid expression. Also, only measures and dimensions are supported.
Nested SQL Functions
A nested SQL query in Data Cloud is a query in another SQL query that’s embedded in a WHERE clause.
Analytical Functions
Data Cloud exposes these analytical SQL functions to use in calculated insights.
Formatting Functions
Data Cloud provides several formatting SQL functions to use with calculated insights.
Math and Statistical SQL Functions
Data Cloud provides several math and statistical SQL functions that you can use in Calculated Insights.
Operators
You can use these SQL operators with calculated insights in Data Cloud.
Joins
A calculated insight can simultaneously access multiple data model objects (DMOs). A calculated insight query that accesses multiple rows of the different DMOs at one time is called a join query. Data Cloud supports four types of joins in a calculated insight: inner, left, right, and full.
SQL Rules in Calculated Insights
When using SQL in calculated insights in Data Cloud, keep these rules and guidelines in mind to create successful functions.
Aggregatable and Non-Aggregatable Metrics
When creating multidimensional metrics in Data Cloud, you can’t aggregate or collapse some Calculated Insights functions or metrics for one or more dimensions. These measures are called non-aggregatable metrics. Examples of non-aggregatable functions include Rank, NTILE, and Case.
